Experiment 1: Design the Smart City Model Using IoT Devices
Aim
To design and develop a smart city model using IoT devices for monitoring and controlling city services such as
street lights, traffic systems, environmental monitoring, and waste management.
Components Required
• Arduino Uno / ESP32
• Wi-Fi Module (ESP8266 if needed)
• LED lights
• LDR sensor
• Ultrasonic sensor
• DHT11/DHT22 sensor
• Breadboard
• Jumper wires
• Buzzer
• Power supply
Theory
A Smart City uses IoT technology to improve the quality of urban services. Sensors collect real-time data from
different areas of the city and send the information to cloud platforms or monitoring systems. IoT helps in smart
traffic control, automatic street lighting, pollution monitoring, waste management, and energy saving.
Procedure
Step 1: Circuit Setup
1. Connect LEDs to Arduino pins for smart street light demonstration.
2. Connect the LDR sensor to detect light intensity.
3. Connect the DHT sensor for temperature monitoring.
4. Connect the ultrasonic sensor for smart parking/waste monitoring.
5. Provide power supply to the Arduino board.
Step 2: Programming
1. Open Arduino IDE.
2. Write the program for reading sensor values.
3. Program the LEDs to turn ON/OFF automatically based on sensor input.
4. Upload the code to Arduino.
Step 3: IoT Communication
1. Connect the ESP32/ESP8266 to Wi-Fi.
2. Send sensor data to a cloud platform such as ThingSpeak or Blynk.
3. Monitor the data in real time.
Step 4: Testing
1. Test automatic street light operation using the LDR sensor.
2. Check temperature values from the DHT sensor.
3. Verify obstacle/distance detection using the ultrasonic sensor.
4. Observe data updates on the cloud platform.
